1. Functional Interface
Definition:

A Functional Interface is an interface with exactly one abstract method.
It can have:

One abstract method (required)

Any number of default or static methods

It is the foundation for lambda expressions in Java 8.

Annotation:
@FunctionalInterface


This annotation is optional but recommended â€” it helps the compiler enforce the rule of having only one abstract method.

âœ… Example: Functional Interface
@FunctionalInterface
interface Calculator {
    int add(int a, int b);  // single abstract method
}

Usage:

Before Java 8 ðŸ‘‡

class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Calculator calc = new Calculator() {
            @Override
            public int add(int a, int b) {
                return a + b;
            }
        };
        System.out.println(calc.add(5, 3)); // 8
    }
}


After Java 8 (with Lambda ðŸ‘‡)

class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Calculator calc = (a, b) -> a + b;
        System.out.println(calc.add(5, 3)); // 8
    }
}


ðŸ’¡ Functional Interface enables Lambda Expression usage!

âš¡ 2. Lambda Expression
Definition:

A Lambda Expression is a short block of code that takes in parameters and returns a value.
It provides a concise syntax to implement functional interfaces.

Syntax:
(parameters) -> expression


or

(parameters) -> { statements; }

âœ… Examples

Example 1: No Parameter

@FunctionalInterface
interface Hello {
    void sayHello();
}

class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Hello h = () -> System.out.println("Hello, Java!");
        h.sayHello();
    }
}


Output:

Hello, Java!


Example 2: With Parameters

@FunctionalInterface
interface MathOperation {
    int operate(int a, int b);
}

class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MathOperation add = (a, b) -> a + b;
        MathOperation multiply = (a, b) -> a * b;

        System.out.println(add.operate(5, 3));      // 8
        System.out.println(multiply.operate(5, 3)); // 15
    }
}


Example 3: With Multiple Statements

@FunctionalInterface
interface Greeting {
    void greet(String name);
}

class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Greeting g = (name) -> {
            System.out.println("Hello, " + name);
            System.out.println("Welcome to Lambda Expressions!");
        };
        g.greet("Atul");
    }
}

ðŸ§© 3. Built-in Functional Interfaces (java.util.function)

Java provides several predefined functional interfaces in java.util.function package.

Interface	Method	Description	Example
Predicate<T>	boolean test(T t)	Tests a condition	(x) -> x > 10
Function<T, R>	R apply(T t)	Converts one type to another	(s) -> s.length()
Consumer<T>	void accept(T t)	Consumes value (no return)	(x) -> System.out.println(x)
Supplier<T>	T get()	Supplies a value	() -> "Hello"
BiFunction<T, U, R>	R apply(T t, U u)	Two inputs â†’ one output	(a,b) -> a+b
Example using Built-in Functional Interfaces
import java.util.function.*;

class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Predicate<Integer> isEven = (n) -> n % 2 == 0;
        Function<String, Integer> length = (s) -> s.length();
        Consumer<String> print = (msg) -> System.out.println(msg);
        Supplier<Double> random = () -> Math.random();

        System.out.println(isEven.test(10)); // true
        System.out.println(length.apply("Atul")); // 4
        print.accept("Hello Functional Interface!"); // prints
        System.out.println(random.get()); // random number
    }
}

âš¡ 4. Why Use Functional Interfaces and Lambdas?
Benefit	Description
Less boilerplate	No need for anonymous inner classes
Readable code	Compact and clean
Functional style	Enables Stream API and method chaining
Parallel execution	Works smoothly with Java Streams
ðŸ§  5. Functional Interface + Lambda = Stream Power

Example:

List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);

nums.stream()
    .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)     // Predicate
    .map(n -> n * n)             // Function
    .forEach(System.out::println); // Consumer


Output:

4
16

âœ… Summary Table
Concept	Description	Example
Functional Interface	Interface with 1 abstract method	Runnable, Callable, Comparator
Lambda Expression	Compact implementation of Functional Interface	(a,b) -> a+b
Built-in FI Examples	Predicate, Function, Consumer, Supplier	Used in Stream API
Annotation	@FunctionalInterface	Optional but recommended
